article.description: Jason Williams atoned for a key  turnover late in regulation by scoring 10 of his 18 points in overtime as the Memphis Grizzlies recovered for a 126-116 victory over the Miami Heat.
article.headline: Grizzlies pile up franchise-record 22 points in OT
article.linkText: Grizzlies blow 21-point lead, then beat Heat with 22 points in OT
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- The Memphis Grizzlies needed to play an extra period to win a game they led by 21.
Williams

Jason Williams scored 10 of his 18 points in overtime and handed out 15 assists Friday night as Memphis defeated the Miami Heat 126-116, despite squandering a 16-point fourth quarter lead. The Grizzlies led by 21 midway through the third period. "It was unbelievable,'' Memphis coach Hubie Brown said. "Nobody can ever say when you come to (a Grizzlies home game) it won't be exciting.'' Williams scored five points early in overtime and the Grizzlies never trailed the rest of the way. Seven Grizzlies finished with double figures and three recorded double-doubles. Pau Gasol had 25 points and 10 rebounds, while Wesley Person scored 19 points and grabbed 14 rebounds as Memphis won for the fourth time in its last five home games. Miami lost its sixth straight on the road. The Heat have dropped eight of their last 10 overall. The Grizzlies didn't make a field goal in the final 6:34 of regulation, due mostly to swarming defense by the Heat. "It would have been a shame if we had lost that game in overtime,'' said Memphis forward Shane Battier, who finished with 16 points. "They made a nice run in the fourth quarter and luckily we got them in overtime.'' Miami's Caron Butler had a dunk and 3-pointer in the final 15 seconds of regulation to send the game into overtime tied at 104. His 3-pointer with 2.8 seconds remaining came from the left wing after a miss by Eddie Jones from almost the same spot. "If it's (against) us, that shot is going in,'' Memphis guard Brevin Knight said of Butler's 3-pointer to send it into overtime. "It's almost like you're starting to expect it. You expect the worst, and if the best happens, then that's good.'' Jones and Butler had 24 points each for the Heat, while Brian Grant added 19 points and 13 rebounds. Travis Best had 18 points, and Malik Allen scored 11. Miami put together a 14-0 fourth-quarter run to cut the lead to 98-94. Memphis went eight straight possessions without scoring during the spurt by the Heat. "We used so much energy coming back,'' Grant said. "We have to sustain it or go beyond it to win.'' Miami hit its first eight shots of the game, connected on 70 percent in the first quarter and 51 percent for the half and still trailed 61-49 at the break. The reason was 11 first-half turnovers that led to 17 points for Memphis. Memphis opened the second half with a 16-7 run, including 10 straight points, to take its biggest lead at 77-56. Miami managed to counter with nine straight points, but still trailed 86-71 at the end of the third quarter. "In overtime, we went back to playing defense like we did the first three quarters,'' Miami coach Pat Riley said. "We weren't intense and didn't stay with it. "They picked us apart. We could score, but we couldn't stop them.''

Game notes
Memphis' 22 points in overtime was three short of the NBA record set by New Jersey against the Clippers in 1996. It was a franchise record, surpassing the 20 overtime points against Portland in 1998. ...The Grizzlies' 37 first-quarter points were the most they've scored in an opening period this season. ... Bolstered by a basketball giveaway and a Family Night package, Memphis had its third sellout of the season. The two previous sellouts were against the Los Angeles Lakers and the Washington Wizards. ... New Grizzlies Mike Miller and Ryan Humphrey still haven't played a home game for Memphis since they were acquired in a Feb. 19 trade with Orlando. Humphrey was put on the injured list a week ago with a sprained ankle. Miller missed his third straight game with back spasms. He is listed as day-to-day. ... Miami, in the midst of a two-week road trip, was playing its third game in four days. ...The 126 points was the most given up by a Riley-coached Miami team.
